<TITLE> Airlines lost more than $1.7 bln by Tuesday - IATA </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 FRANKFURT, Apr 21 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The International Air Transport Association (IATA) estimates that the crisis caused by a volcanic ash cloud above Europe cost airlines revenues of more than $1.7 billion by Tuesday. "At the worst, the crisis impacted 29 percent of global aviation and affected 1.2 million passengers a day," IATA Director General and Chief Executive Giovanni Bisignani said in a statement on Wednesday. He reiterated that the hit by the volcano crisis was bigger than the impact of the 2001 Sept. 11 attacks. On the three days from April 17 to April 19, when the disruptions were the biggest, lost revenues reached $400 million per day, IATA said. Bisignani urged governments to examine ways to compensate airlines for lost revenues. The U.S. government provided $5 billion to compensate airlines after the Sept. 11 attacks, and the European Union also provided assistance to carri
